  "prompt": "What is the best Perl web app framework?",
  "response": "Choosing the \"best\" Perl web app framework can depend heavily on your specific needs and preferences. However, some of the most popular and widely regarded Perl web frameworks include:\n\n1. **Catalyst**: Catalyst is a highly flexible and scalable web application framework, popular for its robustness and extensive features. It supports MVC (Model-View-Controller) design and is highly extensible, allowing developers to add plugins or customize it as needed.\n\n2. **Dancer**: Dancer is known for its simplicity and ease of use, making it a good choice for smaller applications and quick development cycles. It provides clear documentation and has a straightforward DSL (Domain Specific Language) for defining routes and managing requests.\n\n3. **Mojolicious**: Mojolicious is a modern Perl web framework featuring real-time web capabilities, including WebSockets. It aims to be a minimalistic framework but packs a punch with powerful features and support for non-blocking I/O operations.\n\n4. **Plack/PSGI**: While not a web framework itself, Plack is a foundational component for writing web applications in Perl, acting as an abstraction layer between web servers and web applications. It allows developers to use multiple frameworks and is the basis for other frameworks like Catalyst and Dancer.\n\nEach of these frameworks has its own strengths:\n\n- **Catalyst**: Great for large, complex applications requiring a robust feature set.\n- **Dancer**: Ideal for quick development and simpler applications.\n- **Mojolicious**: Excellent for modern web applications requiring real-time capabilities.\n- **Plack/PSGI**: Versatile for creating frameworks and integrating with different web servers.\n\nYour choice should depend on the requirements of your project, familiarity with the framework, and community support available.",
